00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:39.397
She clearly kind of got what
it was I was trying to do,

00:01:39.397 --> 00:01:42.270
even perhaps before
I really realized.

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:45.142
So yes, there's really two
things I'm doing in the book.

00:01:45.142 --> 00:01:48.780
One is telling the story of
the lives of the shell makers.

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:50.780
The animals that
make sea shells.

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:54.920
We all know those beautiful
objects you find on a beach.

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:57.140
You might have picked
them up, taken them home.

00:01:57.140 --> 00:01:58.370
But where do they come from?

00:01:58.370 --> 00:01:59.340
How are they made?

00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:02.150
What happens in the lives
of the creatures that

00:02:02.150 --> 00:02:04.010
left these shells behind?

00:02:04.010 --> 00:02:06.770
So I wanted to tell
partly the story

00:02:06.770 --> 00:02:08.960
about the wonderful
creatures, the mollusks, that

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:10.789
makes these shells.

00:02:10.789 --> 00:02:16.450
Mollusks are really one of the
most strange, smallest, tough,

00:02:16.450 --> 00:02:20.830
ancient, and successful groups
of animals on the planet.

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:22.790
We're talking about
familiar creatures.

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:27.210
Mollusks range from slugs and
snails and squid and octopus.

00:02:27.210 --> 00:02:29.640
And two slightly stranger
things you might not have heard

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:33.540
are things like argonauts and
sea butterflies and chitons,

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:36.400
and weird little things called
[INAUDIBLE] gastros that

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:38.920
live in bottom of the sea, and
frankly just look like worms,

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:40.510
but they are still mollusks.

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:44.730
And they are one of
the most diverse groups

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:47.230
of animals on the planet.

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:50.865
Really, they're only
beaten by the arthropods.

00:02:50.865 --> 00:02:51.820
Another phylum.

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:53.540
These are phyla that
were talking about.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:55.650
Kind of grouping them
in the animal kingdom.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:58.850
And the arthropods
include all the insects.

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:02.320
So they definitely win in
terms of the largest number

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:04.490
of species within a phyla.

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:06.280
There's over a million
species of insects.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:09.460
Alone, most of them are beetles
but mollusks come in, I think,

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:12.160
good second place, frankly.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:15.550
And they are an
incredibly strange bunch

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:19.060
of animals that live all
sorts of different lives.

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:22.250
It's thought there could be
about 50 to 100,000 species

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:26.099
of mollusk alive today that
we've described already.

00:03:26.099 --> 00:03:27.890
And we don't know for
sure, because there's

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:30.740
no-- up until now, there
hasn't been a central catalog

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:32.885
to list all the names of
all the mollusks that have

00:03:32.885 --> 00:03:33.990
been described scientifically.

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:34.920
We're now doing that.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.903
So hopefully we'll get
a bit more of a grasp

00:03:37.903 --> 00:03:41.460
on just how diverse
these animals are.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:45.480
But it's thought by some of the
leading thinkers and scientists

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:47.540
who work on mollusks
that actually there

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:50.470
could be more like
200,000 species, including

00:03:50.470 --> 00:03:52.020
ones we haven't discovered yet.

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:55.020
Including creatures
like these guys.

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:57.430
So these are more micromollusks.

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:00.010
They were found in Papua
New Guinea just last summer.

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:02.790
They are all under 5
millimeters in size.

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:04.670
About the size of your
little fingernail.

00:04:04.670 --> 00:04:08.560
And none of these have been
described scientifically yet.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:10.010
They've just been found.

00:04:10.010 --> 00:04:12.200
They were found during
an expedition lead

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:14.960
by a guy called Philip Bouchet
from the Natural History

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:16.097
in Paris.

00:04:16.097 --> 00:04:18.430
And he basically spends his
life going around the world,

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:20.690
leading expeditions, trying
to find as many mollusks

00:04:20.690 --> 00:04:21.472
as possible.

00:04:21.472 --> 00:04:22.680
People do this kind of thing.

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.310
Scientists focus on a
group and really try

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:27.210
and figure out what's going on.

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:29.685
These were all found
around coral reefs.

00:04:29.685 --> 00:04:32.190
And they're just, just
incredible creatures.

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.225
These are types of
mollusk, snails,

00:04:34.225 --> 00:04:36.610
and clams that no
one's ever seen before.

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:39.290
A clam with pink tentacles
for goodness sake.

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:42.490
And transparent shells so you
can see the skin underneath

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:44.380
is brightly colored.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.580
But these particular
animals, and plenty more

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:50.590
that they find on
these expeditions,

00:04:50.590 --> 00:04:53.620
remain on a museum
shelf undescribed.

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:56.210
They're called orphan
species because we

00:04:56.210 --> 00:05:00.330
lack the expertise to
actually have people sit down

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:01.590
and name individual species.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:05.360
We just don't know about
this kind of diversity.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.810
So there's all this hidden
side to the lives of mollusks.

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:10.945
That was partly what
I wanted to talk about

00:05:10.945 --> 00:05:13.500
in the book was all the
things that we don't yet

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.710
know about this incredible
group of animals,

00:05:15.710 --> 00:05:18.950
including the species
that we haven't yet found.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:20.120
And Philip, I spoke to him.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:22.480
And he's one of the people
who really thinks there could

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:25.170
be 200,000 species of mollusks.

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:26.077
And he should know.

00:05:26.077 --> 00:05:26.910
He looking for them.

00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:28.576
He's finding more and
more all the time.

00:05:28.576 --> 00:05:30.750
Even if all he's really
doing is doing a head count.

00:05:30.750 --> 00:05:31.680
This is something different.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:32.889
We don't know what it is yet.

00:05:32.889 --> 00:05:34.263
We don't know what
might contain.

00:05:34.263 --> 00:05:35.490
We don't know how it lives.

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:38.706
What interesting things that
these animals might be doing.

00:05:38.706 --> 00:05:41.480
And one of the things
I really amazed me when

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:44.800
I was writing the book--
right up until the point where

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:46.390
my published were like, no.

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:47.390
You have to stop now.

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:50.340
You cannot put any more
science into this book.

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.990
There's so many new discoveries
are coming out the mollusk

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:54.715
world, that pretty
much every week I'd

00:05:54.715 --> 00:05:56.423
be like, oh, there's
another cool story I

00:05:56.423 --> 00:05:57.423
want to put in the book.

00:05:57.423 --> 00:06:01.140
Like the fact that limpets
have the toughest teeth

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.490
made out of the toughest
known biological material.

00:06:03.490 --> 00:06:05.320
They've knocked spiders
silk off the perch.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.460
And they figured that
actually because these

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:09.862
are the snails that clamp
themselves to rock and spend

00:06:09.862 --> 00:06:11.820
their lives scraping the
rock with their teeth,

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.880
they've evolved this incredibly
strong material in their teeth.

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:16.810
So it was like, that
has to go in the book.

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:18.720
Somewhere, we have to get it in.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.710
And then I think actually
just the last thing

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:22.126
I did manage to
get into the book,

00:06:22.126 --> 00:06:26.700
the last story was about
how cone snails-- these

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:29.200
are poisonous sea snails
that live in the tropics.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:34.010
They are notorious for having
incredibly diverse and complex

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:37.300
toxins that they use to hunt
all sorts of animals, including

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:37.960
fish.

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:40.325
And there are a few species
that if they sting a human,

00:06:40.325 --> 00:06:42.560
they will actually kill them.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:44.690
Bit of an overkill,
but there's reasons

00:06:44.690 --> 00:06:46.620
why we think they're
such powerful hunters.

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:49.078
So that they can actually-- a
tiny snail that slowly slides

00:06:49.078 --> 00:06:51.140
along the sea bed,
has the ability

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:54.670
to eat fast moving fish,
which is kind of incredible.

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:57.510
And a new discovery just
came out a few months

00:06:57.510 --> 00:06:59.920
before the book came
out that they in fact,

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.480
use insulin as part
of their weaponry.

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:05.700
So that the only animal we
know that's kind of evolved

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:07.720
this hormone so that it
essentially knocks out

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:10.230
its prey by giving
it a dose of insulin

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:12.710
so that their blood sugar
levels drop, and they faint.

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:14.260
And they can then
eat these fish.

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:15.957
That's just really cool.

00:07:15.957 --> 00:07:19.890
So there were lots of
incredible, cool, amazing, mind

00:07:19.890 --> 00:07:23.260
blowing discoveries coming
out of the mollusk world.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:25.032
And that was a really
big part of what

00:07:25.032 --> 00:07:27.440
I wanted to do in the book
was to capture this excitement

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:28.850
of what we're discovering.

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:31.850
And the applications of a
lot of this, this science,

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:33.391
is exciting too.

00:07:33.391 --> 00:07:34.890
The cone snail
venoms that have been

00:07:34.890 --> 00:07:36.810
used to develop
medicines, that have been

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:39.800
used in biomedical research.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.606
The fact that razor
clams- I don't

00:07:41.606 --> 00:07:44.775
know if you've ever seen the
long, thin shell shells you

00:07:44.775 --> 00:07:45.650
might see on a beach.

00:07:45.650 --> 00:07:47.549
They burrow themselves
in the sand,

00:07:47.549 --> 00:07:49.340
but they're much more
efficient to doing it

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:51.670
than just their muscles
and their shape,

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:54.880
and the strength of their
shell would suggest.

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:57.970
And researchers have figured
out that they actually

00:07:57.970 --> 00:07:59.750
have this clever
technique of creating

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:02.540
little pools of quicksand
around them as they dig down.

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:07.000
And it's incredibly
efficiently way of burrowing.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.680
And this could lead to the next
generation of underwater robots

00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:12.550
that can fix things
to the sea bed.

00:08:12.550 --> 00:08:15.760
Even undersea cables
for the internet.

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:19.400
They could be fixed down
by these robots inspired

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:20.922
by razor clams.

00:08:20.922 --> 00:08:22.630
There's tons of cool
stuff about mollusks

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:25.064
that I was trying to
talk about in the book.

00:08:25.064 --> 00:08:29.890
And what I wanted to capture too
was some of the big discoveries

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:32.850
and some of the big
questions that scientists

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:35.180
have thought about when it
comes to shells and mollusks

00:08:35.180 --> 00:08:36.870
over the years.

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:41.260
And one of the big ones is
the shape of their shells.

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:43.624
How is it that shells are made?

00:08:43.624 --> 00:08:45.915
They've got these-- many of
them are beautiful spirals.

00:08:45.915 --> 00:08:47.410
I call my book
"Spirals in Time."

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:50.290
I guess because I wanted
to allure to the idea

00:08:50.290 --> 00:08:52.890
that these things have been
around for a long time.

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.770
And spiraling around.

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:58.750
These calcium carbonate spirals
have been around for probably

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:00.040
for half a billion years.

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:02.160
We think mollusks first
evolved in the oceans

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:04.000
about 500 million years ago.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.960
But how do they
make their shells?

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:07.760
And why are there so
many different shapes?

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:10.740
And in lots of great
thinkers have put their mind

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.250
to try and work out what's
the mathematics that lie

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:15.720
behind shells and shell making?

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:18.180
One of the simplest
parts of a shell,

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:22.080
of a mollusk's spiraling shell,
is the logarithmic spiral.

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:24.510
A spiral that expands
at a constant rate.

00:09:24.510 --> 00:09:28.080
[INAUDIBLE] came up with
this idea of a log spiral.

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.330
And if you cut through a
chambered nautilus, which

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:33.340
is this shell here, you get
a pretty good approximation

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:37.130
to that logarithmic
spiral in two dimensions.

00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:39.360
And if you look at lots
of different mollusks,

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:42.160
many of the gastropods with the
spiraling shells, the snails,

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:44.820
as well as these
the natutilises,

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.730
and various other,
the bivalves too,

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:50.000
clams and so on, they do still
have spirals in their shells.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.790
We'll come to that.

00:09:52.790 --> 00:09:54.780
What about into
three dimensions?

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:57.240
That was the next big
question that scientists

00:09:57.240 --> 00:09:58.280
were thinking about.

00:09:58.280 --> 00:09:59.863
Mathematicians and
philosophers wanted

00:09:59.863 --> 00:10:03.477
to figure out how could you
make a three dimensional shell?

00:10:03.477 --> 00:10:04.643
It's all very well the same.

00:10:04.643 --> 00:10:06.080
You've got these two dimensions.

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:07.913
The log spiral is really
important actually,

00:10:07.913 --> 00:10:10.580
because no matter how
big or small it is,

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:11.510
it's the same shape.

00:10:11.510 --> 00:10:13.930
And that is a key
rule to making shells

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:18.131
is that if they're tiny
of if they're huge,

00:10:18.131 --> 00:10:19.380
they will stay the same shape.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:21.960
So mollusks keep their
shelves their whole life,

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:23.960
unlike crustaceans,
the crabs and lobsters

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:26.240
will shed their shells
and grow new ones.

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:29.220
Mollusks keep the same ones,
just growing bigger and bigger.

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:34.620
But they stay the shape,
even if they're tiny or huge.

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:36.260
But how about three dimensions?

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:39.110
So it was the turn
of the 20th century,

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:41.540
there was a guy called
Darcy Wentworth Thompson,

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:44.940
who wrote a book called
"On Growth and Form."

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:47.550
And he was really thinking
about shapes in nature.

00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:50.540
And how can mathematics
describe the shapes

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:53.880
of a splash, or a deer's
antler, or indeed,

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.814
the shape of a three
dimensional spiraling shell?

00:10:56.814 --> 00:10:59.700
And he came up with the
idea that perhaps you

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:03.420
create these 3D shells by
spinning a two dimensional

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:05.686
shape in three dimensions.

00:11:05.686 --> 00:11:07.310
And so essentially
what he's looking at

00:11:07.310 --> 00:11:13.130
is having a central axis around
which maybe a circle, a flat

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:14.990
circle spins around.

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:17.210
And it can either do
so in the same plane,

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:20.780
or it can drop down that axis.

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:24.910
The walls of the shell can
overlap each other or not.

00:11:24.910 --> 00:11:27.905
And perhaps it would
only take three--

00:11:27.905 --> 00:11:29.681
this is running away from me.

00:11:29.681 --> 00:11:34.217
Stop it, stop it-- three
or four simple rules

00:11:34.217 --> 00:11:35.925
to actually make all
the different shells

00:11:35.925 --> 00:11:36.890
that you see in nature.

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:38.990
So he came up with this idea,
just a theoretical idea,

00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:39.900
he couldn't test it.

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:41.690
All he had was paper and pencil.

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:43.990
Could you make all of
the sells we see nature

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:48.110
with three simple rules of this
single, circle spinning three

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:51.370
dimensions, how tall it
gets along that axis,

00:11:51.370 --> 00:11:55.010
and how much those worlds
overlap each other?

00:11:55.010 --> 00:11:58.290
These ideas were picked up 40
years later by a paleontologist

00:11:58.290 --> 00:12:01.120
called David Raup
who did something

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:03.820
unusual for a paleontologist
certainly at the time.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:05.430
He used a computer.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:08.340
As he took these
equations from Thompson,

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:12.527
and he plugged them into a
mainframe IBM 1790 computer.

00:12:12.527 --> 00:12:14.402
The sort of thing that
was at the time-- this

00:12:14.402 --> 00:12:15.690
was in the '60s.

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.090
The '50s and '60s
was intended to be

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:21.750
used for designing aircraft
and nuclear reactors,

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:24.480
but I think he managed
to get some down time.

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:27.320
He was at Johns Hopkins
University in Maryland,

00:12:27.320 --> 00:12:30.380
and he used this
computer to build shells.

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:35.280
And to see if these simple rules
that Thompson had come up with,

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:36.810
whether you really
could make all

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:40.290
the different shells that
you see in three dimensions.

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:41.280
And he did.

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:43.520
And the output he had
from his computer work

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:46.160
was all 2D plots,
which were then

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:48.460
realized by an artist
in three dimensions.

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:51.010
But we can now have
a look at a mock

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:53.713
up of what the output of his
model would have looked like.

00:12:53.713 --> 00:12:55.046
And we're going to let that run.

00:12:55.046 --> 00:12:57.100
I think it's incredibly
beautiful and mesmerizing.

00:12:57.100 --> 00:12:59.558
So what we're doing here is
just changing these parameters,

00:12:59.558 --> 00:13:05.220
the height, the expansion, the
rate at which the shell flares

00:13:05.220 --> 00:13:06.270
ope as well.

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:08.270
And just by changing
these three parameters,

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:11.510
you do actually get incredible
diversity of shells emerging

00:13:11.510 --> 00:13:14.737
from those simple rules.

00:13:14.737 --> 00:13:17.320
The rest of your shells can be
explained through fairly simple

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:18.430
mathematics.

00:13:18.430 --> 00:13:20.200
You get the clam form
a spiraling shell.

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:22.890
You wouldn't expect
that, but it pops up.

00:13:22.890 --> 00:13:26.370
And what Raup did
was he created what's

00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:30.810
come to be known as The
Museum of All Possible Shells.

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:38.240
And populated by these shells
created from these equations.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:41.560
And what seemed to be all
these different, endless forms

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:43.646
that you see in nature.

00:13:43.646 --> 00:13:46.380
But the really
surprising thing he found

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:48.850
was that the Museum
of All Possible Shells

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:51.249
actually isn't full
of real shells.

00:13:51.249 --> 00:13:53.040
If you look at the
shell that have actually

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:56.090
evolved in the past
through fossils,

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:59.020
and through what's
alive today, there

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:00.730
are lots of parts of this space.

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:03.313
If you think about it as being
this actual space where there's

00:14:03.313 --> 00:14:05.845
three parameters on the
next y and zed axis,

00:14:05.845 --> 00:14:08.576
there are large parts of this
space that aren't occupied.

00:14:08.576 --> 00:14:11.400
And those shells
haven't evolved.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:18.120
And it's raised this
question about this

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.460
is a theory called
theoretical morphospace.

00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:24.295
The possibilities of
what organisms could be.

00:14:24.295 --> 00:14:27.256
What shapes they could be
and what they actually are.

00:14:27.256 --> 00:14:29.130
And why there's a
difference between the two.

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:32.200
So evolution hasn't
taken mollusks and shells

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:36.730
to all the possibilities
that these simple rules could

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:37.230
lead to.

00:14:37.230 --> 00:14:39.220
Some of these shells
just haven't existed.

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:40.830
Raup pointed out
that some of the ones

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:44.030
he made in his computer
wouldn't have worked.

00:14:44.030 --> 00:14:45.750
There were clams
that wouldn't open.

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:47.500
There were some that
would just be flimsy,

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:52.550
and they wouldn't be competitive
out there in the wild ocean

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:54.150
and in places where
mollusks live.

00:14:54.150 --> 00:14:55.086
But there were
plenty of shells that

00:14:55.086 --> 00:14:56.252
seemed to be perfectly good.

00:14:56.252 --> 00:14:59.490
And there seems no reason
why they haven't evolved.

00:14:59.490 --> 00:15:02.260
And people expanded
this idea out now.

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:06.090
And we've built museums of
all possible fish and plants

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:08.120
and all different
types of organisms

00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:10.100
that you can look
at their morphology

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:14.160
and see what potential
shapes they could be.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:16.327
And then compare that
to what we actually see.

00:15:16.327 --> 00:15:17.910
And again and again
you see this limit

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:19.340
of what evolution's created.

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:22.230
Of what evolution's thrown
up, and what potentially

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:23.420
could occur.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:25.350
And discussions are going on.

00:15:25.350 --> 00:15:27.550
There is this division
between some people who

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:30.555
think that ultimately yes, all
these shells could and would

00:15:30.555 --> 00:15:34.775
evolve if the situation
arose that that shell would

00:15:34.775 --> 00:15:37.397
be well adapted to a
particular condition.

00:15:37.397 --> 00:15:39.730
And there are others who think
that actually, maybe, no.

00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:42.090
Then that's the
evolution-- genetically

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:45.220
there isn't the material that
would ever evolve these shells.

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:46.800
It just would never happen.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:49.730
And the discussions go on.

00:15:49.730 --> 00:15:51.485
That's one of the
big questions I

00:15:51.485 --> 00:15:53.790
look into on a bit more
detail in the book of how

00:15:53.790 --> 00:15:54.500
shells evolve.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:55.708
Why they're different shapes.

00:15:55.708 --> 00:15:58.550
And why we don't actually
see all the potential shells

00:15:58.550 --> 00:16:03.540
that mathematics suggest
could exist in the world.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:06.520
So that's the life
part of the subtitle.

00:16:06.520 --> 00:16:08.470
There's also the after life.

00:16:08.470 --> 00:16:11.600
And this isn't the
bit of the book

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:14.640
where I talk about snail
ghosts or any kind of belief

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:15.390
in the after life.

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:19.760
It's really just my
desire to talk about how

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:21.570
humans have used shells.

00:16:21.570 --> 00:16:23.380
So after the animals
inside that make

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:25.490
them have died and
long gone, and they've

00:16:25.490 --> 00:16:29.206
left behind these
empty shells, we

00:16:29.206 --> 00:16:30.581
do all sorts of
things with them.

00:16:30.581 --> 00:16:31.960
And there's incredible,
long, history.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:33.418
Pretty much to the
dawn of humanity

00:16:33.418 --> 00:16:35.510
that people have seen
shells, they've found them,

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:37.200
and put them to
all sorts of uses.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:39.930
Both practical and
incredibly deep

00:16:39.930 --> 00:16:42.720
symbolism and
meaning in seashells.

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:46.080
I was really amazed researching
the book at just how broad

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:49.134
and how universal these
beliefs in shells are.

00:16:49.134 --> 00:16:50.550
There are symbols
of sex and death

00:16:50.550 --> 00:16:54.802
and birth and power
and money, and cultures

00:16:54.802 --> 00:16:58.385
all over the world, and
even far, far from the ocean

00:16:58.385 --> 00:17:00.410
have these incredibly
strong beliefs in shells.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:02.720
So I wanted to tell
some of those stories.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:06.402
I partly wanted to try and
reinstate some of the grandeur

00:17:06.402 --> 00:17:10.619
and some of the wonder
and magnificence of shells

00:17:10.619 --> 00:17:12.030
in human lives.

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:18.849
Because today, I think shells
have got more of a reputation

00:17:18.849 --> 00:17:21.869
for being fairly-- they're
cheap, throw-away trinkets.

00:17:21.869 --> 00:17:27.489
They're emblems of ocean that
we can buy from a seaside store,

00:17:27.489 --> 00:17:28.850
or perhaps we find ourselves.

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:31.110
We don't really pay them
that much attention.

00:17:31.110 --> 00:17:35.315
And people make
things like-- this

00:17:35.315 --> 00:17:39.510
is the kind of thing people
use shells for these days--

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:42.600
Make things like
this, and also this.

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:44.790
I found this on sale on eBay.

00:17:44.790 --> 00:17:47.141
She's got lovely,
lovely headdress on.

00:17:47.141 --> 00:17:51.410
Oh dear, now it's
running away again.

00:17:51.410 --> 00:17:54.130
What I wanted to
do was tell stories

00:17:54.130 --> 00:17:56.526
of how people have used
shells in the past in ways

00:17:56.526 --> 00:17:58.600
that are far more magnificent.

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:02.242
So this guy here is
about 7,000 years old.

00:18:02.242 --> 00:18:03.990
I don't know why
this is running away.

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:05.460
Hang on a second.

00:18:05.460 --> 00:18:07.910
I'm going to just do this a
different way so it stops--

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:09.380
stops going too quickly.

00:18:12.860 --> 00:18:15.620
I wanted to tell stories of
how people have used shells,

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:16.715
not to make comedy frogs.

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:25.335
So this is a great
found in Bulgaria.

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:32.490
And about 7,000 years old.

00:18:32.490 --> 00:18:35.560
They're called
the old Europeans.

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:37.960
Don't you want to know
why it's doing that?

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:40.100
AUDIENCE: I think you've
got auto advance on.

00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:44.766
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:19:02.462 --> 00:19:03.462
HELEN SCALES: Excellent.

00:19:07.510 --> 00:19:10.291
Stories of shells being
used in human lives.

00:19:10.291 --> 00:19:11.790
There's this
incredibly rich history

00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:15.280
of the beliefs and
symbolism of shells.

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:19.500
This chap is the leader
of the Varna community.

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:23.220
These guys lived in Europe
about 7,000 years ago.

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:25.280
Up until this point,
when this was discovered

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:31.000
in the 1970s, this grave in the
city of the dead in Bulgaria,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:32.760
it was thought that
the old Europeans were

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:36.270
quite an egalitarian group,
and that they were mostly just

00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:37.256
nomadic farmers.

00:19:37.256 --> 00:19:39.930
There was no sign up until
that point of any elites

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:42.160
who were coming in
charge, and that society

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:43.730
was fairly even and equal.

00:19:43.730 --> 00:19:45.890
And they found a
grave where a guy

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:49.490
covered in gold and with
all sorts of jewelry,

00:19:49.490 --> 00:19:52.390
including some very
beautiful shell jewelry.

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:56.890
And that's why I wanted to talk
about this particular case.

00:19:56.890 --> 00:19:58.950
Around this guy's
upper arm, you can

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:02.391
see on one side he's got
bangles, including a white one.

00:20:02.391 --> 00:20:04.390
And that's made from a
shell called spondylitis.

00:20:04.390 --> 00:20:06.172
It comes from a long
way from this part.

00:20:06.172 --> 00:20:07.630
It doesn't come
from the Black Sea,

00:20:07.630 --> 00:20:10.120
but from the Mediterranean.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:11.830
And there was this
long distance trade

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:13.460
in these shells
called spondylitis

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:16.610
that were carved into
beautiful objects, all the way

00:20:16.610 --> 00:20:18.230
across Europe up to Paris.

00:20:18.230 --> 00:20:20.400
And often what
was done with them

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:23.359
is they were carved into
bangles that people wore.

00:20:23.359 --> 00:20:24.900
And I think there's
even been studies

00:20:24.900 --> 00:20:26.712
to show that some
of these bangles

00:20:26.712 --> 00:20:28.920
were put on to people's arms
when they were children,

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:31.382
and then they grow into them,
and couldn't take them off

00:20:31.382 --> 00:20:32.084
again.

00:20:32.084 --> 00:20:34.500
This particular one though,
it was just really intriguing.

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:38.032
So it was carved
from this big shell.

00:20:38.032 --> 00:20:39.240
They're called spiny oysters.

00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:40.810
That's another name
for these shells.

00:20:40.810 --> 00:20:42.421
In life, they're
covered in spines.

00:20:42.421 --> 00:20:43.920
But cut them through
and they've got

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:46.940
this beautiful,
bright white shell.

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:50.340
And carved into a bangle,
broke it, and then

00:20:50.340 --> 00:20:52.552
fixed with gold plates.

00:20:52.552 --> 00:20:54.010
And that's what
this guy's wearing.

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:55.644
We don't know why they did that.

00:20:55.644 --> 00:20:57.060
There's various
other remains that

00:20:57.060 --> 00:21:01.330
seem to be deliberately broken
of these shells left in graves.

00:21:01.330 --> 00:21:05.500
There's some significance
behind this particular shell.

00:21:05.500 --> 00:21:08.090
It was always the same
species that was being used.

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:11.430
And then it just disappeared,
and they stopped being used.

00:21:11.430 --> 00:21:13.410
It was about 6,000 years
ago, and that's it.

00:21:13.410 --> 00:21:14.921
No more spondylitis.

00:21:14.921 --> 00:21:17.490
There was a parallel trade
in spondylitis shells

00:21:17.490 --> 00:21:19.954
in the Americas, with the
Aztecs and the Mayans.

00:21:19.954 --> 00:21:21.370
They were using
spondylitis shells

00:21:21.370 --> 00:21:23.830
for decorations and money.

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:26.280
They were carving
statuettes of humans,

00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:27.795
giving them to
children, taking them

00:21:27.795 --> 00:21:29.295
to the tops of the
highest mountains

00:21:29.295 --> 00:21:32.000
and leaving them there,
as human sacrifices.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.500
So there were all these
incredible, significant stories

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:35.596
about shells.

00:21:35.596 --> 00:21:38.279
And so I tell some of
those stories in the book.

00:21:38.279 --> 00:21:43.580
And hopefully try to reinstate
some of the sense of mystery

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:45.480
and wonder about
what shells are.

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:47.080
And I think one of
the reasons people

00:21:47.080 --> 00:21:48.496
value them so much
is because they

00:21:48.496 --> 00:21:52.550
come from this dark, deep
ocean where they're full

00:21:52.550 --> 00:21:54.400
of sea monsters and
things we can't see.

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:56.379
But these beautiful
objects wash up on beaches.

00:21:56.379 --> 00:21:58.545
And people have always
wondered where they come from

00:21:58.545 --> 00:22:02.830
and how they're made, and
hold them in great meaning.

00:22:02.830 --> 00:22:03.460
Oh.

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:06.887
Now I've broken it entirely.

00:22:06.887 --> 00:22:07.387
Sorry.

